				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \begin{aligned} max f(x) = \sum _{i=1}^{n}p_ix_i, i = 1, 2,\ldots , n \\ s.t. \sum _{i=1}^{n}c_{ij}x_i \le b_j, j = 1, 2,\ldots , m \\ x_i \in \{0, 1\} \end{aligned} \end{aligned}$$\end{document}where n and m represent the numbers of items and constraints, and pi\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_i$$\end{document} is the ith capacity. It is mainly divided into three categories:
0–1 KP: each item can only be selected once at most.
 Multi-dimensional KP (MKP): if we have n items and m knapsacks with capacities not necessarily the same, knapsacks will be filled at the same time.
Dynamic KP: the capacity, weight and profit of knapsacks dynamically change.

